Synchronization, \'91lean\'92 and \'91just-in-time\'92 Different terms are used to describe what here we call lean synchronization. Our definition \'96 \'91lean synchronization aims to meet demand instantaneously, with perfect quality and no waste\'92 \'96 could also be used to describe the general concept of \'91lean\'92, or \'91just-in-time\'92 (JIT). The concept of \'91lean\'92 stresses the elimination of waste, while \'91just-in-time\'92 emphasizes the idea of producing items only when they are needed. But all three concepts overlap to a very large degree, and no definition fully conveys the full implications for operations practice. Here we use the term lean synchronization because it best describes the impact of these ideas on flow and delivery.\
