\uc0\u10095  What are the broad approaches to managing improvement? \u9679 \
\
What we have called \'91the broad approaches to improvement\'92 are relatively coherent collections of some of the \'91elements\'92 of improvement. The four most common are total quality management (TQM), lean, business process re-engineering (BPR) and Six Sigma.\
\
\uc0\u9679 \
\
BPR is a typical example of the radical approach to improvement. It attempts to redesign operations along customer-focused processes rather than on the traditional functional basis. The main criticisms are that it pays little attention to the rights of staff who are the victims of the \'91downsizing\'92 which often accompanies BPR, and that the radical nature of the changes can strip out valuable experience from the operation.\
\
\uc0\u9679 \
\
Total quality management was one of the earliest management \'91fashions\'92 and has suffered from a backlash, but the general precepts and principles of TQM are still influential. It is an approach that puts quality (and indeed improvement generally) at the heart of everything that is done by an operation.\
\
\uc0\u9679 \
\
Lean was seen initially as an approach to be used exclusively in manufacturing, but has become seen as an approach that can be applied in service operations. Also lean, when first introduced, was radical, and counter-intuitive. The idea that inventories had a negative effect, and that throughput time was more important than capacity utilization, was difficult to accept by the more traditionally minded. So, as lean ideas have been gradually accepted, we have likewise come to be far more tolerant of ideas that are radical and/or counter-intuitive.\
\
\uc0\u9679 \
\
Six Sigma is \'91A disciplined methodology of defining, measuring, analysing, improving, and controlling the quality in every one of the company\'92s products, processes, and transactions \'96 with the ultimate goal of virtually eliminating all defects\'92. First popularized by Motorola, it was so named because it required that the natural variation of processes ( \{ 3 standard deviations) should be half their specification range. In other words, the specification range of any part of a product or service should be \{ 6 the standard deviation of the process. Now the definition of Six Sigma has widened beyond its statistical origins. It should be seen as a broad improvement concept rather than a simple examination of process variation, even though this is still an important part of process control, learning and improvement.\
\
\uc0\u9679 \
\
There are differences between these improvement approaches. Each includes a different set of elements and therefore a different emphasis. They can be positioned on two dimensions. The first is whether the approaches emphasize a gradual, continuous approach to change or a more radical \'91breakthrough\'92 change. The second is whether the approach emphasizes what changes should be made or how changes should be made.\
